possibility-that new media will lead to new kinds of "worldmaking." This provocative volume brings together the best new work of scholars within such diverse fields as history, sociology, anthropology, film, media studies, and art. Whether examining the inauguration of a virtual community on the website Second Life or investigating the appropriation of biotechnology for transgenic art, this collection highlights how mediated practices have become integral to global culture; how social practices have emerged out of computer-related industries; how contemporary apocalyptic narratives reflect the anxieties of a U.S. culture facing global challenges; and how design, play, and technology help us understand the histories and ideals behind the digital architectures that mediate our everyday actions.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspects. 0aIdentity (Psychology) and mass media. 0aMass media and art. 0aMass media and culture. 0aMass media and globalization. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAneesh, A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHall, Lane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPetro, Patrice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813551944423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813551944.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKAL